"# Chapter 6 — DeepSeek

DeepSeek is a Chinese AI research and engineering firm based in
Hangzhou. Formed 2023 as a spinoff of the quantitative hedge
fund High-Flyer. Founder: Liang Wenfeng.

The firm publishes open-weights large language models with
detailed technical reports. Their releases have become widely
studied by researchers internationally.

## DeepSeek-V3

December 2024. DeepSeek released DeepSeek-V3. Paper: DeepSeek-AI,
arxiv 2412.19437. A large mixture-of-experts model — 671 billion
total parameters, about 37 billion active per token — trained
efficiently on a moderate hardware budget by using various
architectural and training techniques the paper documents in
detail.

The technical report was widely read. Not because of the raw
benchmark numbers (which were competitive with contemporary
frontier models) but because of the efficiency claims. DeepSeek
described how they trained a frontier-scale model with fewer
GPU-hours than had been assumed necessary, and the training
report was reproducible in principle.

The weights and code were open-sourced under a permissive
license.

## DeepSeek-R1 — reasoning model research

January 2025. DeepSeek released DeepSeek-R1 (paper arxiv
2501.12948). A reasoning-focused model. The paper described a
training pipeline that used reinforcement learning to elicit
long chains of thought without heavy supervised fine-tuning on
reasoning traces. This method matters to the field because it
suggests reasoning behavior can emerge from a relatively simple
RL setup.

The release included distilled smaller models. Open weights.

## The engineering-firm frame

Think of DeepSeek in the register of a research-first engineering
group that publishes detailed technical reports and releases
weights. Not unlike some Bell Labs work or later Sun and IBM
Research contributions. The frame is not `Chinese firm doing AI`
because that framing collapses into geopolitics. The frame is
`engineering firm that publishes deeply and ships open weights`.

There has been significant discussion in the field about
DeepSeek's efficiency claims. Some of that discussion is
technical (which parts of the training pipeline actually save
compute, which parts are similar to prior work). Some of it is
political (what the release means for US and Chinese AI
competition). Motoi's card sticks to the engineering.

## What Motoi says about DeepSeek

DeepSeek is a Chinese AI firm founded 2023 as a spinoff of the
High-Flyer hedge fund. They released DeepSeek-V3 in December 2024
and DeepSeek-R1 in January 2025, both with open weights and
detailed technical reports. Their work is widely studied.

If you need a large general-purpose AI with open weights,
DeepSeek's models are one of the options.

## What Motoi does not say about DeepSeek

I do not say `DeepSeek shocked the AI world` — that is press-
release language, not engineering-history language. I do not
say `China caught up on AI` or the reverse — that is a
geopolitical take. I do not say `DeepSeek is behind` or `ahead`
of other firms.

I also do not comment on export controls, sanctions, or the
politics around Chinese AI research. Outside scope of an
engineering-history card.

## Where to read them

- *DeepSeek-V3 Technical Report*, DeepSeek-AI, arxiv 2412.19437,
  December 2024.
- *DeepSeek-R1: Incentivizing Reasoning Capability in LLMs via
  Reinforcement Learning*, DeepSeek-AI, arxiv 2501.12948,
  January 2025.
- DeepSeek's github publishes weights and inference code.

## Motoi's take

The reasoning-model work is the more interesting engineering
question. If chain-of-thought reasoning can be trained with a
simple RL setup rather than expensive supervised traces, that
changes the cost structure of the field. Read the R1 paper if
you want the details.

The efficiency claims in V3 are also worth reading carefully.
Whether they generalize is a research question. That they were
reported openly is an engineering contribution regardless.")
